english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent Off to the Venerable Yingam upon His Travels
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Venerable Yingam set forth to wander the four directions, and along his way, renowned scholars and versifying monks bestowed upon him many poems. He brought them with him, showed them to me tucked within his sleeve, and requested that I write a preface for them.

    I said to him: "In the Tang dynasty, Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan were the greatest scholars of their age. Yet the Buddhist monk Wen Zhang obtained all their poems, and his name has endured a thousand years, remaining imperishable alongside Han and Liu—such is the power of poetry and prose. Though Wen Zhang achieved great glory, the writings of Han and Liu tower supreme across all ages. Why then does every later generation take Han Yu as their master? Because he did not flatter Wen Zhang. By refusing to flatter, he spoke the Way directly and plainly, criticizing what was wrong. Whether Wen Zhang received this with joy or burned with anger, we cannot know. Yet Liu Zongyuan, himself a Confucian, still attacked Han Yu through the authority of others. So Wen Zhang's anger is understandable. But Han Yu merely devoted himself to illuminating the Way—did he concern himself with Liu's slander or Wen Zhang's wrath?

    Today, the Venerable Yingam has received poems from many worthy scholars. But how many can match Han Yu's refusal to flatter?

    Alas! The Way originates in Heaven's principle and manifests in human relations. By it, Yao and Shun became rulers; by it, Yi Yin and the Duke of Zhou became ministers; Confucius and Mencius possessed it while dwelling in humble stations; Zengzi and Minzi obtained it while serving their parents. Each, encountering their station, fulfilled their role completely—this is how sages complete human relations and preserve Heaven's principle.

    In the great affairs of ritual and music, punishment and government, coronation, marriage, and mourning rites; in the small matters of conjugal life, dwelling, farming, and sericulture—the Way pervades everywhere and nothing is too minute to neglect. Thus the Way of we Confucians rests upon the ordinary affairs of daily life, where each thing has its order: from kinship springs affection, from reverence springs respect. Grasp the square rule and quadrangles form; turn the compass and circles take shape. The practice is not extraordinary, yet its verification is most certain. When applied, it brings good order; when transmitted, it brings no harm.

    Before the Yin and Zhou dynasties, this Way was preserved and all under Heaven was ordered. After the Qin and Han, the Way was lost and all under Heaven fell into chaos. In between, the teachings of Laozi and Buddha arose, with Buddhism becoming especially vigorous. For a thousand years it has spread across the six directions; its followers multiply and its devotees grow ever more reverent. Its Way could be called widely practiced—yet why does all under Heaven remain poorly ordered?

    Because it severs human relations as the highest achievement and seeks the Way apart from things. This is like dismantling the rule and compass while still hoping for squares and circles—how could it ever succeed?

    Venerable One, you seek the Way neither in the principles of body and mind, nature and destiny, nor in the constant human relations of daily life. Instead you wander restlessly through the four directions. I fear you resemble one on a stray horse, knowing not where to return.

    Because I admire Han Yu's refusal to flatter, I dare speak this to you. Whether you receive it with joy or burn with anger is for you alone to choose. What have I to regret?"
  footnotes:
    - Han Yu (768-824) and Liu Zongyuan (773-819) were prominent Tang dynasty scholars and writers known for their literary reforms and philosophical positions on Confucianism.
    - Wen Zhang (文暢) was a Buddhist monk contemporary with Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan who was known for his literary talents and whose poetry was admired by major scholars of the age.
    - The 'square rule and compass' (矩規) is a metaphor for fundamental principles—just as these tools generate geometric forms, proper principles generate proper order in society.
    - Gwon Geun employs the dialogue format to present a Confucian critique of Buddhism, arguing that Buddhist teachings disconnect practitioners from human relationships and practical life, the foundations of moral order.
